post_cb({"2990924": {"ParentId": "2990760", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>It looks like a bug to me. The initialization (<code>int test = {1,2,3};</code>) is fine, but as far as I can see, nothing in the standard allows the assignment.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "179910", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "2990924", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2010-06-07T15:44:24.130", "LastActivityDate": "2010-06-07T15:44:24.130"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_2990760_2990760_0": {"section_id": 6181, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "length": 10}}, "n3337": {"so_2990760_2990760_0": {"section_id": 5942, "quality": 1.0, "length": 12}}, "n4659": {"so_2990760_2990760_0": {"section_id": 7683, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "length": 10}}}, "2990760": {"CommentCount": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "2990924", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2013-12-04T15:23:09.033", "LastEditorUserId": "500104", "CreationDate": "2010-06-07T15:24:31.377", "LastActivityDate": "2012-07-13T00:34:21.513", "LastEditDate": "2012-07-13T00:34:21.513", "ViewCount": "511", "FavoriteCount": "2", "Title": "Is assignment of braced-init-list to an array correct?", "Id": "2990760", "Score": "9", "Body": "<p>The standard says, under 5.17/9</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_2990760_2990760_0\">A braced-init-list may appear on the right-hand side of<br>\n      - an assignment to a scalar [...]<br>\n      - an assignment defined by a user-defined assignment operator [..]</br></br></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>While in GCC 4.5.1-pre9999, I can compile this (using -std=c++0x, NOT -std=gnu++0x)</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nint main()\n{\n        int test[] = {1,2,3};\n        std::cout &lt;&lt; test[0] &lt;&lt; test[1] &lt;&lt; test[2];\n        test = {4,5,6};\n        std::cout &lt;&lt; test[0] &lt;&lt; test[1] &lt;&lt; test[2] &lt;&lt; std::endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>and it prints <code>123456</code>. Is GCC correct here?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><g++><language-lawyer><standards-compliance>", "OwnerUserId": "273767", "AnswerCount": "1"}});